<div1 type="letter" n="1900-07-30">
<head>Report from William M. Black to the Adjutant General, July 30, 1900</head>
<pb n="1" id="f02073001"/>
<opener>
File under Reed - Electrozone<lb/>
(Black)<lb/>
Division of Cuba,<lb/>
Office of Chief Engineer.<lb/>
<dateline>
Havana, <date value="1900-07-30">July 30, 1900.</date>
</dateline>
The Adjutant General,<lb/>
Division of Cuba.<lb/>
<salute>Sir:-</salute>
</opener>
<p>I have the honor to submit the following comments on the report<lb/>
made by Major Walter Reed, Surgeon, U. S. Army, on the Electrozone<lb/>
Plant in this City, under date of April 20th.</p>
<p>Major Reed's well known reputation as a bacteriologist, and<lb/>
his known care in experiments, entitle his opinion as to the germici-<lb/>
dal qualities of Electrozone to great weight, and there can be no<lb/>
doubt as to the results he obtained from his experiments.</p>
<p>In his comments on the plant, however, there are certain<lb/>
statements which are misleading and which should be corrected.</p>
<p>The enclosed report from Mr. Rowe, in charge of the plant<lb/>
(Inclosure &ldquo;A&rdquo;), shows that during the time in which Dr. Reed was<lb/>
making his tests, the plant was run at a decided disadvantage. Mr.<lb/>
Rowe states that Dr. Reed was informed of this, but if so it evidently<lb/>
made little or no impression. At this <add>present</add> time, with 24 hours run, there<lb/>
is an average daily product of 35,000 gallons of Electrozone, of<lb/>
which 4000 gallons are of 100 grs. strength and 31,000 gallons of 150<lb/>
grains strength, at a cost of 2.5 mills and 2.75 mills per gallon<lb/>
respectively. For a fuller statement of results and cost, attention<lb/>
is invited to the enclosed extract from the annual report (Inclosure<lb/>
&ldquo;B&rdquo;).</p>
<p>It seems beyond a doubt that at the time of Dr. Reed's visit,<lb/>
<pb n="2" id="f02073002"/>
- 2 -<lb/>
a lack of judgment, if not carelessness, was shown in the management<lb/>
of the plant, and that Electrozone was sent out below the required<lb/>
strength. If such was the case, the blame should be placed on the<lb/>
personnel, where it belongs.</p>
<p>In Table II of Dr. Reed's report, under the head of<lb/>
strength of current, &ldquo;1000 gallons of sea water&rdquo; should read &ldquo;2000<lb/>
gallons of sea water&rdquo;.</p>
<p>The statements regarding the relative cost of chloride of<lb/>
lime disinfectant and of electrozone are also in error.</p>
<p>The cost of chloride of lime here has varied from four<lb/>
to seven cents per pound, the last obtained being four cents.<lb/>
Last year, at times, the higher rate had to be paid. The chloride<lb/>
of lime as obtained here commercially contains 23.06 % of available<lb/>
chlorine, - not 35 %, the theoretical strength given by Dr. Reed. Dr.<lb/>
Reed's attention was invited by me to this increased cost and de-<lb/>
creased strength when here. Hydrochloric acid costs here six cents<lb/>
per pound.</p>
<p>Again, Dr. Reed's estimate of deterioration of plant<lb/>
is 10 % per annum. Accepting these figures, it is certainly wrong<lb/>
in making a comparison of relative costs of electrozone and of other<lb/>
disinfectants to charge in the entire cost of the plant to one year.</p>
<p>Page <unclear><del>7</del><add>21</add></unclear> of the report should then be amended to read as<lb/>
follows:-</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is believed that the following calculations will<lb/>
<pb n="3" id="f02073003"/>
- 3 -<lb/>
&ldquo;closely approximate the relative cost of Chlorinated lime and Electro-<lb/>
&ldquo;zone as disinfectants:</p>
<p>
<table rows="2" cols="2">
<row><cell>&ldquo; To 1 lb. of chloride of lime (7000 grains)</cell><cell>4 cents.</cell></row>
<row><cell>&ldquo; 1 " of hydrochloric acid,</cell><cell>6 cents.</cell></row>
</table>
</p>
<p>&ldquo; 7000 grains of chloride of lime containing 23.06 %, or 1614.2 grains<lb/>
&ldquo; of available chlorine, would make 11.06 gallons of a disinfectant,<lb/>
&ldquo;having a strength of 0.250 % or 146 grains of chloride per gallon.<lb/>
&ldquo;Debucting 1.06 gallons as loss of chlorine in making the preparation,<lb/>
&ldquo;we have:-</p>
<p>
<table rows="4" cols="2">
<row><cell>To 10 gallons of disinfectant, 1 lb. of lime,</cell><cell>4 cents.</cell></row>
<row><cell>" " " " 1&sol;2 " hyd. acid,</cell><cell>3 "</cell></row>
<row><cell></cell><cell>-------------</cell></row>
<row><cell>Total,</cell><cell>7 cents.</cell></row>
</table>
</p>
<p>&ldquo; or at a cost of 7 mills per gallon, or, for 24000 gallons a cost of<lb/>
&ldquo;$168.00 per day.</p>
<p>&ldquo; Since July 1, 1899, to March 31, 1900, - 234 working days - the<lb/>
&ldquo;total expenditure would have been $39,312.00 for sufficient chloride<lb/>
&ldquo;of lime and hydrochloric acid to have supplied a disinfectant having<lb/>
&ldquo;146 grains of available chlorine per gallon.</p>
<p>&ldquo; On the other hand, we have the following:-</p>
<p>
<table rows="5" cols="2">
<row><cell>&ldquo; 1&sol;10 of plant,</cell><cell>$ 7,500.</cell></row>
<row><cell>&ldquo; Int. at 6 % for 9 mos.,</cell><cell>3,375.</cell></row>
<row><cell>&ldquo; Daily expenses, $37. for 234 working days,</cell><cell>8,658.</cell></row>
<row><cell></cell><cell>--------------------</cell></row>
<row><cell></cell><cell>$ 19,533.</cell></row>
</table>
</p>
<p>&ldquo; as the cost of supplying daily for 234 working days, 24,000 gallons<lb/>
<pb n="4" id="f02073004"/>
- 4 -<lb/>
&ldquo;of Electrozone, having no particular standard of strength as regards<lb/>
&ldquo;available chlorine, but certainly of a less strength (see table 1)<lb/>
&ldquo;than <unclear>[unclear]</unclear>150 %.&rdquo;</p>
<p>This would have been a more fair statement of the<lb/>
status than that given in the report, although it is not believed<lb/>
nor proved that the strength through the year averaged less than<lb/>
.150 %.</p>
<p>It is not believed to be necessary to apologize<lb/>
for the erection of the plant. The conditions in Havana fully war-<lb/>
ranted the action taken. The death rate and the reports of total<lb/>
sick show conclusively that the various measures taken were effective, -<lb/>
and the supply and use of Electrozone is one. I do regret that I<lb/>
did not expend a slightly greater sum for the plant, so as to have<lb/>
installed engines and boilers of greater first cost, but of a type<lb/>
more economical in running expenses.</p>
<closer>
<salute>Very respectfully,</salute>
<signed>W. M. Black</signed>
Major, Corps of Eng'rs U. S. A.<lb/>
Chief Engineer.<lb/>
</closer>
</div1>
<div1 type="document" n="1900-07-05">
<head>Report: Review of the Most Salient Points of Dr. Reed's Report, by G. C. Rowe, July 5, 1900</head>
<pb n="5" id="f02073005"/>
<p>Inclosure &ldquo;A.&rdquo;</p>
<p><hi>COPY</hi>.</p>
<p>Electrozone Plant, July 5th, 1900.</p>
<p>REVIEW OF THE MOST SALIENT POINTS OF DR. REED'S REPORT.</p>
<p>Electrozone is put to seven different uses in the City of<lb/>
<unclear>Havana</unclear>, viz: sewer disinfection; house disinfection by the Sani-<lb/>
tary Department; disinfection of fresh earth on public and private<lb/>
works; street disinfection by sprinkling; disinfection and deodoriz-<lb/>
ing of the &ldquo;Night Soil&rdquo; carts, rendering them inoffensive; disin-<lb/>
fection of Stables by private owners; and last but not least in<lb/>
relation to the greatest good to the greatest number, it is used as<lb/>
a medicine by the people, both as an antiseptic wash and as an inter-<lb/>
nal drug for various stomach and intestinal diseases. That Elec-<lb/>
trozone is not superflous in sprinkling the street is evinced<lb/>
by the quick cessation of bad odors in the muddy streets where it<lb/>
is applied.</p>
<p>The low tests taken by Dr. Reed are the result of the re-<lb/>
duxtion in the capacity of the plant on the days in which Dr. Reed<lb/>
made his test, first by Dr. Reed himself, and 2nd by the visit of<lb/>
Secretary Root. Dr. Reed required one dynamo out of the four<lb/>
nearly every day in order to make solutions of various strengths;<lb/>
many of these solutions were in the neighborhood of 200 gr. per gal;<lb/>
and a solution of over 300 gr. per gal. was produced for Scy.<lb/>
Root's visit. This reduction in the amount of power used on the<lb/>
same output in gallons naturally caused a reaction upon the strength<lb/>
of the Electrozone produced.</p>
<p>While Dr. Reed did not use any of the machinery on the date<lb/>
of his first visit, Monday March 11th, still his visit was announced<lb/>
<pb n="6" id="f02073006"/>
- 2 -<lb/>
in the morning early and one dynamo was at once reserved for making<lb/>
Electrozone of a special strength upon which the visitor might form<lb/>
an opinion favorable to Electrozone; and this reservation of the<lb/>
dynamo was made in spite of the fact that the day was Monday and the<lb/>
output was always increased about 4 or 5 thousand gallons, and to<lb/>
meet this demand we were accustomed to start an hour earlier every<lb/>
Monday. After the first two or three visits from Dr. Reed, we be-<lb/>
gan running 9 hours per day instead of 8 as the necessary comple-<lb/>
ment to his reduction of our available forces.</p>
<p>Thus it can readily be seen that Dr. Reed's tests<lb/>
were not a sample of every day's run under normal conditions.</p>
<p>In Table 2 of Major Reed's report, he mentions<lb/>
&ldquo;3000 to 3500 Amp. acting upon 1000 gal. of sea water for 8 hours&rdquo;.<lb/>
He should have said 2000 gal. of sea water.</p>
<p>At the time of this test, Major Reed was informed that<lb/>
our regular fireman was sick and the substitute, being unaccustomed<lb/>
to our boilers, was unable to maintain more than 60 lbs. boilers<lb/>
pressure, while under normal conditions, our regular fireman keeps<lb/>
from 90 to 100 lbs. constantly. Hence Dr. Reed's observation in<lb/>
regard to the amperage of the remaining three sets was wholly one<lb/>
<unclear>of</unclear> an occasion. The attendant of the vats and dynamos was instructed<lb/>
to keep the load on Major Reed's dynamo constant at 3000 Amp., and<lb/>
it was with difficulty that he did it, as the varying steam pres-<lb/>
sure necessitated the taking the entire load off some of the other<lb/>
machines at times, and at other times loading them up again to<lb/>
prevent the current from going above 3000 Amp. on his machine.</p>
<pb n="7" id="f02073007"/>
<p>- 3 -</p>
<p>The fact that 3000 Amp. was selected as the current for<lb/>
Major Reed's experiment does not mean that that is the power of<lb/>
the dynamos, but rather that 3000 Amp. is the normal working load<lb/>
when both engines are working at their best. The dynamos could<lb/>
run on 4500 Amprs. if the engines could pull that load. As it is<lb/>
the load always runs above 3000 Amp. on the remaining three machines<lb/>
when one is thrown out for the purpose of cleaning the electrodes.<lb/>
This increase on the three working dynamos amounts to 1000 Amp.<lb/>
apiece, thus compensating for the 3000 Amp. thrown out.</p>
<p>While Major Reed mentions the fact that the trial run of<lb/>
the entire plant made Mar. 27 was conducted during a heavy rain<lb/>
storm, he does not mention the effect that the abnormal atmospheric<lb/>
conditions had upon our fires. In spite of the fact that the<lb/>
regular fireman was at his post and working like a Trojan he could<lb/>
not make the short chimney keep up a good draught so that the<lb/>
regular working pressure of 100 lbs. was impossible.</p>
<p>Dr. Reed's attention was called to this and he was<lb/>
asked to postpone his trial until more favorable weather. This<lb/>
dependence on the atmospheric conditions has since been overcome by<lb/>
installing a mechanical draught system which enables us to maintain<lb/>
the regular working pressure under all conditions.</p>
<p>While Prof. Woolf claims that the theoratical value of<lb/>
the Amp. Hour is 20 gr. of available chlorine per set of electrodes,<lb/>
he does not say that it is ever attainable in practice.</p>
<p>According to Bunsen; &ldquo;the force of the current must al-<lb/>
ways be great enough to surmount the affinities of the elements<lb/>
<pb n="8" id="f02073008"/>
- 4 -<lb/>
in the compound&rdquo;. From this it is readily seen that if a pair of<lb/>
electrodes were supplied with a force just equal to that of the<lb/>
affinities of the elements we wish to separate no action would re-<lb/>
sult.</p>
<p>The additional force that is afterwards applied to do<lb/>
chemical work represents the difference between the theorecal<lb/>
equivalent and the practical attainment. As the result of our<lb/>
practice of 12 gr. per Amp. Hour - or more nearly 12.22 - was ob-<lb/>
tained by a calculation involving the quantity of 3000 Amp. working<lb/>
for three hours, for one tank only, Dr. Reed's statement is likely<lb/>
to be erroneously construed as he failed to multiply this result<lb/>
by two, or even to mention that the same amount of work was done<lb/>
in the other tank.</p>
<p>--------------------------------------------------</p>
<p>Report on chlorine solution produced by the action of<lb/>
Hydrochloric Acid upon a solution of Calcium Hypochlorite:</p>
<p>Test No. 1, June 9th, 1900.</p>
<p>Chloride of Lime taken from the bottom of a barrel at Los<lb/>
Fosos, 1 lb. of Lime was dissolved in 10 gal. of water, resulting in<lb/>
a milky solution smelling strongly of Hypochlorous acid. Many small<lb/>
lumps remained floating on top of the liquid, remaining perfectly<lb/>
dry until mashed between the thumb and finger.</p>
<p>Test by the arsenous acid method gave 230% or 134.55 gr.<lb/>
per gal. for the solution, or a total of 1345.5 gr. of available<lb/>
Cl. in the pound of lime taken; which gives 19.22% of available<lb/>
chlorine contained in the dry lime. This solution was comparatively<lb/>
<pb n="9" id="f02073009"/>
- 5 -<lb/>
stable. Test taken every two hours showed no appreciable diminution<lb/>
of available Cl. until the end of 14 hours when the percentage of<lb/>
available Cl. in the solution was found to be .227% or 132.48 gr.<lb/>
per gal. This solution was alkaline to litmus and was not very ac-<lb/>
tive in bleaching qualities as it bleached blue litmus only after<lb/>
long exposure.</p>
<p>Test No. 2. June 15th, 1900.</p>
<p>One lb. of a second sample taken, made a solution, in five<lb/>
gal. of water, that contained 252.54 gr. per gal. of available Cl.,<lb/>
making the percentage of available Cl. in the dry chloride 18.08.</p>
<p>To the 5 gal. of solution made with the above sample, 5 gal.<lb/>
of water containing 1&sol;2 lb. of commercial hydrochloric acid was<lb/>
added. Free chlorine was copiously evolved, the odor of which<lb/>
was so strong as to cause the attendant stirring the mixture to leave<lb/>
his place for fear of being suffocated. After the bubbles of chlorine<lb/>
gas had ceased to escape, the solution was tested and found to con-<lb/>
tain only 109.71 gr. of Cl. per gal; less than half it had before,<lb/>
indicating that considerable Cl. had been lost by adding the acid.<lb/>
The bleaching properties were more pronounced, the Cl. acted so<lb/>
promptly that it appeared to be in a nascent state. The milky color<lb/>
of the Hypochlorite solution was entirely dispelled by the addition<lb/>
of the hydrochloric acid and a clear green liquid was the result.</p>
<p>The green color was due entirely to free chlorine gas in<lb/>
solution as was afterwards proven by allowing sunlight to fall upon<lb/>
a test tube containing some of the solution when hydrochloric acid<lb/>
was produced with the liberation of oxygen.</p>
<pb n="10" id="f02073010"/>
<p>- 6 -</p>
<p>As the ten gallons of solution was found to be still<lb/>
slightly alkaline to litmus 1&sol;4 lb. more of HCl was added with the<lb/>
usual result of much foaming and free chlorine. The resulting<lb/>
solution was acid to litmus and the available chlorine was only<lb/>
105.57 grs. per gal.</p>
<p>Test No. 3, June 25th, 1900.</p>
<p>A sample of Calcium Hypochlorite taken from a newly<lb/>
opened barrel in Los Fosos was found to contain 23.06 % of available<lb/>
Chlorine. (The U. S. Pharmacopoeia specified that, <unclear>&ldquo;.35 grm.</unclear><lb/>
of Chlorinated lime be titurated with 50 cc of water and carefully<lb/>
transferred, together with the <hi>washings</hi>, into a flask, &ldquo;in making<lb/>
the test for available chlorine in the commercial chloride, and<lb/>
further says that it should contain 35%. Owing to the insoluble<lb/>
nature of a part of the chloride of lime, and the fact that the dis-<lb/>
infectant required must be a solution, the chloride contained in the<lb/>
<hi>washings</hi> must be considered as non available. Hence the tests made<lb/>
were of the available chlorine that went into solution, and not<lb/>
the total amount of available chlorine contained in the dry lime.<lb/>
This partly accounts for the low percentage found.)</p>
<p>One pound of this 23.06 % Hypochlorite was dissolved in<lb/>
ten gallons of water. Test gave 161.42 gr. per Gal. or .276 %.<lb/>
Three-fourths of a Lb. of hydrochloric acid was then added and the<lb/>
solution tested after effervescence had ceased. The following<lb/>
shows loss of available chlorine in mixing, as well as loss after mix-<lb/>
ing, compared with loss in Electrozone.</p>
