<p>At 12 M. the next day after the above mentioned chlorine solution<lb/>
was made the sun light shone in the open barrel in which it was stand-<lb/>
ing, thereby enabling the free chlorine to decompose the water and form<lb/>
hydrochloric acid; which was sufficiently plentiful to redden blue lit-<lb/>
mus at 2 P.M. As soon as the available Cl. was all gone, which hap-<lb/>
pened in about 39 hours, a sample was placed in a bottle having a glass<lb/>
stopper and set aside to be used in determining the percentage of HCl<lb/>
present. This I was enabled to do July 6th upon receipt of a normal<lb/>
solution of caustic soda from the City chemist.</p>
<p>The solution contained in the above mentioned bottle con-<lb/>
tained .272 % of real hydrochloric acid thus showing that nearly all<lb/>
the available Cl. had gone to form hydrochloric acid.</p>
